the broad range of texts which featured the Eastern Mediterranean in this era. Goran Stanivukovic highlights how eroticism within prose romances, particularly homoerotic desire, facilitated commercial, cross-ethnic, and cross-cultural interactions, shaping European knowledge and conceptions of the Mediterranean and the Ottoman Empire. Through his careful examination of these lesser known works, Stanivukovic sheds important light on early modern trade, Mediterranean politics, and the changing meaning of masculinity in an age of commercial expansion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish prose literaturey16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish prose literaturey17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aRepublicanismxHistory. 0aRomances, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 70(DE-588)4008764-50(DE-627)1046295840(DE-576)208878173aBürger2gnd 70(DE-588)4076232-40(DE-627)1060833840(DE-576)209201274aPolitisches Engagement2gnd 70(DE-588)4115751-50(DE-627)1058119550(DE-576)209495766aRepublikanismus2gnd 70(DE-588)4125554-90(DE-627)1057393400(DE-576)209577525aTugend2gnd 70(DE-588)4129611-40(DE-627)1057086740(DE-576)209611944aPolitische Identität2gnd 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261891640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442618916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442618916.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles